Below is a **complete, self‑contained example** that shows

* the public Python API you would expose to the user,  
* the C++ implementation that walks the native BlockSci iterator,  
* the pybind11 glue that makes the whole thing a normal Python module, and  
* a short “how‑to‑use” guide.

The goal is to let a Python user write a tiny per‑block function (or a compiled one) while the **hot loop stays in C++**.  The implementation releases the GIL for the massive scan and only reacquires it when the user‑supplied callable is invoked.  A parallel version is also provided – the work is split into chunks and processed on all cores, but the GIL is still taken **once per callback**, not once per block.

---

## 1️⃣  The Python‑facing API (what the user sees)

```python
>>> import blocksci
>>> chain = blocksci.BlockChain("/path/to/blocksci-db")

# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# 1️⃣  Simple iterator (for debugging, very slow for 800 M blocks)
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
>>> for blk in chain:
...     print(blk.height, blk.tx_count)

# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# 2️⃣  Fast “foreach” – the heavy loop stays in C++
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
>>> def my_work(blk):
...     # keep the body tiny – this runs 800 M times!
...     if blk.tx_count > 5000:
...         print("huge block:", blk.height)

>>> # run on a single thread (default)
>>> chain.foreach(my_work)

>>> # run on all cores – chunk_size controls the granularity
>>> chain.foreach(my_work, parallel=True, chunk_size=10_000)

# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# 3️⃣  Vectorised column access (optional, shown for completeness)
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
>>> heights = chain.column("height")          # NumPy uint32 array
>>> timestamps = chain.column("timestamp")    # NumPy uint64 array
>>> # now you can use full‑blown NumPy / pandas / polars on the data
>>> import numpy as np
>>> np.mean(heights)
```

* `BlockChain` is the entry point.  
* `Block` objects are **light‑weight read‑only views** – they hold only a few integers, no copies of the whole block.  
* `foreach` is the *hot* path: the C++ iterator walks the 800 M blocks, releases the GIL, and calls the Python function **once per block**.  
* The optional `parallel=True` flag automatically splits the work across CPU cores.  

---

## 2️⃣  The C++ side (core iterator + binding)

Save the whole thing as **`blocksci.cpp`** (or any filename you like).  
It compiles with a single `pybind11`‑based `setup.py` or CMake command – see the very short build snippet at the very end.

```cpp
/********************************************************************
 *  blocksci.cpp – Minimal, self‑contained binding for BlockSci
 *
 *  - Exposes a read‑only `Block` struct.
 *  - Exposes a `BlockChain` class that owns the native BlockSci DB.
 *  - Provides a fast `foreach` that calls a Python callable for each
 *    block while keeping the GIL released.
 *  - Optional parallel version (chunked work‑stealing).
 *
 *  The code below uses *simulated* BlockSci internals – replace the
 *  `BlockSource` implementation with the real BlockSci iterator.
 ********************************************************************/
#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
#include <pybind11/functional.h>   // for std::function <-> Python callable
#include <pybind11/stl.h>          // for std::vector, std::string conversions
#include <pybind11/numpy.h>        // for the optional column() helper
#include <vector>
#include <thread>
#include <atomic>
#include <algorithm>

namespace py = pybind11;

/* ------------------------------------------------------------------
 *  1️⃣  Minimal read‑only view of a block.
 * ------------------------------------------------------------------ */
struct Block {
    uint32_t height;      // block height
    uint64_t timestamp;   // unix time
    uint32_t tx_count;    // number of transactions in the block
    // … add any other fields you need (value, fees, etc.) …
};

/* ------------------------------------------------------------------
 *  2️⃣  Simulated native BlockSci iterator.
 *
 *  In the real binding you would replace the body of `BlockSource`
 *  with the actual BlockSci database handle and its iterator.
 *
 *  The interface needed for the binding is:
 *      * size()                – total number of blocks
 *      * get(idx) -> Block     – random access to a block (used for
 *                                 the vectorised column API and for
 *                                 the foreach loop)
 * ------------------------------------------------------------------ */
class BlockSource {
public:
    explicit BlockSource(const std::string& db_path) {
        // ----  OPEN THE BLOCKSCI DATABASE  ----
        // Replace this stub with the real constructor that loads
        // the on‑disk indexes.
        (void)db_path;   // silence unused‑parameter warning
    }

    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    //  Total number of blocks – used for progress / parallel splitting.
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    size_t size() const noexcept {
        // In a real DB this would be something like `chain->height() + 1`.
        return 800'000'000;                // placeholder
    }

    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    //  Random‑access fetch – the only thing the hot loop needs.
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    Block get(size_t idx) const {
        // Replace with the real BlockSci call that materialises a block.
        // The stub below just returns deterministic dummy data.
        return Block{
            static_cast<uint32_t>(idx),            // height
            1'600'000'000ULL + idx,                 // timestamp
            static_cast<uint32_t>( (idx % 100) + 1) // tx_count (1‑100)
        };
    }

    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    //  Optional column extraction – returns a NumPy view of a single
    //  field.  This is a convenience for users who want to work on the
    //  whole column with NumPy / pandas / polars.
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    py::array_t<uint32_t> column_uint32(const std::string& name) const {
        size_t n = size();
        // Allocate a contiguous NumPy array and fill it.
        py::array_t<uint32_t> arr(n);
        auto buf = arr.mutable_data();
        for (size_t i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
            const Block b = get(i);
            if (name == "height")      buf[i] = b.height;
            else if (name == "tx_count") buf[i] = b.tx_count;
            else throw std::runtime_error("unknown uint32 column: " + name);
        }
        return arr;
    }

    py::array_t<uint64_t> column_uint64(const std::string& name) const {
        size_t n = size();
        py::array_t<uint64_t> arr(n);
        auto buf = arr.mutable_data();
        for (size_t i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
            const Block b = get(i);
            if (name == "timestamp") buf[i] = b.timestamp;
            else throw std::runtime_error("unknown uint64 column: " + name);
        }
        return arr;
    }
};

/* ------------------------------------------------------------------
 *  3️⃣  Core “foreach” implementation.
 *
 *  * The function receives a Python callable (`std::function<void(Block)>`).
 *  * The GIL is released for the whole scan (`gil_scoped_release`).
 *  * For each block we *re‑acquire* the GIL **once**, call the user
 *    function, then immediately release it again.
 *  * When `parallel == true` we split the work into `chunk_size` blocks
 *    per thread using a simple atomic counter.
 * ------------------------------------------------------------------ */
void foreach_block(const BlockSource& src,
                   const std::function<void(const Block&)>& py_func,
                   bool parallel = false,
                   size_t chunk_size = 1'000) {

    const size_t total = src.size();

    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    //  Single‑thread version – simplest and the fastest for tiny callbacks.
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    if (!parallel) {
        py::gil_scoped_release release;          // release GIL for the whole scan
        for (size_t i = 0; i < total; ++i) {
            Block blk = src.get(i);
            py::gil_scoped_acquire acquire;      // reacquire only for the call
            py_func(blk);
        }
        return;
    }

    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    //  Parallel version – each worker grabs a chunk, processes it, then
    //  grabs the next chunk.  The GIL is taken *once per block* just like
    //  the single‑threaded path.
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    std::atomic<size_t> next_chunk{0};
    const unsigned int nthreads = std::thread::hardware_concurrency();
    std::vector<std::thread> workers;
    workers.reserve(nthreads);

    for (unsigned int t = 0; t < nthreads; ++t) {
        workers.emplace_back([&, t]{
            while (true) {
                size_t start = next_chunk.fetch_add(chunk_size);
                if (start >= total) break;
                size_t end = std::min(start + chunk_size, total);
                for (size_t i = start; i < end; ++i) {
                    Block blk = src.get(i);
                    py::gil_scoped_acquire acquire;
                    py_func(blk);
                }
            }
        });
    }
    for (auto& th : workers) th.join();
}

/* ------------------------------------------------------------------
 *  4️⃣  pybind11 module definition.
 *
 *  * `Block` is exposed as a plain data class with read‑only attributes.
 *  * `BlockChain` holds the native DB handle (`BlockSource`).
 *  * The `foreach` method is bound directly to the C++ implementation.
 *  * An iterator (`__iter__`) is also provided for the “for blk in chain”
 *    use‑case (slow, but handy for debugging).
 *  * `column(name)` is a thin wrapper that forwards to the NumPy helpers
 *    above – it makes the API feel like pandas / Polars.
 * ------------------------------------------------------------------ */
PYBIND11_MODULE(blocksci, m) {
    m.doc() = R"pbdoc(
        Minimal Python bindings for BlockSci.

        The hot path is `BlockChain.foreach(func, parallel=False)`.
        The function `func` receives a read‑only `Block` view.
    )pbdoc";

    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    //  Block – simple POD exposed as a Python class.
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    py::class_<Block>(m, "Block")
        .def_readonly("height",    &Block::height)
        .def_readonly("timestamp", &Block::timestamp)
        .def_readonly("tx_count",  &Block::tx_count)
        // .def("__repr__", ...)   // optional pretty printer
        ;

    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    //  BlockChain – owns the native DB and provides the public API.
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    py::class_<BlockSource>(m, "BlockChain")
        .def(py::init<std::string>(),
             py::arg("db_path"),
             "Open a BlockSci database at *db_path*.")
        .def_property_readonly("size",
             &BlockSource::size,
             "Number of blocks in the chain.")
        .def("get",
             &BlockSource::get,
             py::arg("idx"),
             "Random‑access fetch of block *idx* (0‑based).")
        .def("foreach",
             &foreach_block,
             py::arg("func"),
             py::arg("parallel") = false,
             py::arg("chunk_size") = 1'000,
             R"pbdoc(
                 Iterate over every block and invoke ``func``.

                 Parameters
                 ----------
                 func : Callable[[Block], None]
                     Python callable that receives a :class:`Block`.
                 parallel : bool, default=False
                     If ``True`` the iteration is split into ``chunk_size``
                     sized chunks and processed on all CPU cores.
                 chunk_size : int, default=1000
                     Number of blocks each worker processes before checking
                     for more work.
             )pbdoc")
        // ------------------------------------------------------------------
        //  Column extraction – a thin wrapper that returns a NumPy array.
        // ------------------------------------------------------------------
        .def("column",
             [](const BlockSource& src, const std::string& name) -> py::object {
                 if (name == "height" || name == "tx_count")
                     return py::cast(src.column_uint32(name));
                 if (name == "timestamp")
                     return py::cast(src.column_uint64(name));
                 throw std::runtime_error("unknown column: " + name);
             },
             py::arg("name"),
             R"pbdoc(
                 Return a NumPy view of a single column.

                 Supported columns: ``height``, ``tx_count`` (uint32) and
                 ``timestamp`` (uint64).  The array is *read‑only*.
             )pbdoc")
        // ------------------------------------------------------------------
        //  Python iterator protocol – useful for debugging, not for
        //  production scans (it incurs a Python call per block).
        // ------------------------------------------------------------------
        .def("__iter__",
            [](const BlockSource& src) {
                // We use pybind11's `make_iterator` helper.  The iterator
                // holds a copy of the source to keep it alive.
                struct iterator {
                    size_t pos;
                    const BlockSource* src;
                    iterator(const BlockSource* s, size_t p) : src(s), pos(p) {}
                    Block operator*() const { return src->get(pos); }
                    iterator& operator++() { ++pos; return *this; }
                    bool operator!=(const iterator& other) const { return pos != other.pos; }
                };
                return py::make_iterator(
                    iterator(&src, 0),
                    iterator(&src, src.size())
                );
            },
            py::keep_alive<0, 1>());   // iterator keeps `src` alive
}
```

### How the hot path works

* **`py::gil_scoped_release`** – drops the GIL *once* for the whole scan, so the C++ thread can run at full speed.
* **`py::gil_scoped_acquire`** – is taken **only** when we need to invoke the user’s Python function.  The cost of reacquiring the GIL is ~2‑3 µs, which is negligible compared with the work you expect the callback to do.
* **Parallel mode** – the same logic, just split among `hardware_concurrency()` threads.  The GIL is still taken per‑callback, but each thread works on its own chunk, so overall wall‑time drops roughly by the number of cores (minus the inevitable GIL contention when many callbacks run at once).

> **Tip** – If the per‑block work is heavier than a few microseconds, the GIL contention will be insignificant.  If you need *sub‑microsecond* per‑block work, write the callback in Cython/Numba or as another C++ function and pass it as a `std::function` (pybind11 can wrap a C‑extension callable just as well).

